05791nam a22007695i 9780801464171DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014641717 a10.7591/97808014641712doi  a(DE-B1597)478432  a(OCoLC)979968165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD6077.2.U62bN39 2016 7aHIS0360802bisacsh04a306.3615097477509172231 aOsterud, Nancy Grey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPutting the Barn Before the House :bWomen and Family Farming in Early Twentieth-Century New York /cNancy Grey Osterud. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b12 halftones, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Gender, Power, and Labor -- t1. Putting the Barn Before the House -- t2. Women’s Place on the Land -- tPart II. Farming and Wage-Earning -- t3. “Buying a Farm on a Small Capital” -- t4. The Transformation of Agriculture and the Rural Economy -- tPart III. The Division of Labor and Relations of Power -- t5. Sharing and Dividing Farm Work -- t6. Intergenerational and Marital Partnerships -- t7. Wage-Earning and Farming Families -- t8. Negotiating Working Relationships -- tPart IV. Organizing the Rural Community -- t9. Forming Cooperatives and Taking Collective Action -- t10. Home Economics and Farm Family Economies -- tConclusion: Gender, Mutuality, and Community in Retrospect -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPutting the Barn Before the House features the voices and viewpoints of women born before World War I who lived on family farms in south-central New York. As she did in her previous book, Bonds of Community, for an earlier period in history, Grey Osterud explores the flexible and varied ways that families shared labor and highlights the strategies of mutuality that women adopted to ensure they had a say in family decision making. Sharing and exchanging work also linked neighboring households and knit the community together. Indeed, the culture of cooperation that women espoused laid the basis for the formation of cooperatives that enabled these dairy farmers to contest the power of agribusiness and obtain better returns for their labor. Osterud recounts this story through the words of the women and men who lived it and carefully explores their views about gender, labor, and power, which offered an alternative to the ideas that prevailed in American society.Most women saw "putting the barn before the house"—investing capital and labor in productive operations rather than spending money on consumer goods or devoting time to mere housework—as a necessary and rational course for families who were determined to make a living on the land and, if possible, to pass on viable farms to the next generation. Some women preferred working outdoors to what seemed to them the thankless tasks of urban housewives, while others worked off the farm to support the family. Husbands and wives, as well as parents and children, debated what was best and negotiated over how to allocate their limited labor and capital and plan for an uncertain future. Osterud tells the story of an agricultural community in transition amid an industrializing age with care and skill.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFamily farmsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNanticoke Valley. 0aFamily farmszNew York (State)zNanticoke ValleyxHistoryy20th century. 0aFarm lifexHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNanticoke Valley. 0aFarm lifezNew York (State)zNanticoke ValleyxHistoryy20th century. 0aRural women